etymologies: late Middle English (in prefect (sense 2)): from Old French, from Latin praefectus, past participle of praeficere ‘set in authority over’, from prae ‘before’ + facere ‘make’. prefect (sense 1) dates from the early 19th century

definitions: in some schools, a senior student authorized to enforce discipline.
shortDefinitions: (in some schools) senior pupil who is authorized to enforce discipline

definitions: a chief officer, magistrate, or regional governor in certain countries
shortDefinitions: chief officer, magistrate, or regional governor in certain countries

definitions: a senior magistrate or governor in the ancient Roman world

examples.text: Avitus was prefect of Gaul from AD 439

shortDefinitions: senior magistrate or governor in ancient Roman world
